@Iwan Morgan (and others of course) here's a quick 15 min vid I made (sorta run-on, but you'll get the point) that covers most of how I use Wavelab day-to-day. To @Eric Martin point though, I do intake QC in RX and final QC listen/dither/whatever in RX as well

https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fo/noc0zlrykgftkhfr7p0bt/AGGoXe3RKa-gUbbztjLFXwE?rlkey=ecuatquh5re4pmdzocavh1feh&dl=0

This is just an in-the-box flow but covers most of the main points (for me). For analog you can either add your external effect to the clip (which annoyingly stops from being able to hear a reference track). How I capture usually though is to put the clip on a feed track (which is a reference track) send that to the delivery track, and record it in. This way you don't have to render in real time when you bounce or if a small edit, say a different fade or whatever, is needed.

@masteredbyjack Your golden rule is still true for me - ( is what I’m doing making the record feel better to me or not? Is it becoming more of what it wants to be?) - is what I strive for. Generally, I am working on stuff with organic tracks, and my moves tend to make the record feel better, make it more of what it wants to be. This song was a bit less organic, but still based in that world - so YES ! I was absolutely seeking outside approval to make me feel better about using the limited ref. I needed a consult haha. Was def freaked out about loosing gig , hence hitting the legend Ruairi.

"Do you think you would have approached using the ref any differently if you knew it was just some kid in a bedroom, or would you have still trusted that it was still the move to use it?" - Man, this is such a good question. I have always fantasized about how cool it would be to sit down to work every day and have everything completely wiped so IDK what came from who - like have someone name everything "A" "B" and just work and then have them "decode" it to be the right artists that get their files, but I have no idea whos is whos while working. Obviously this is not realistic but certainly would be a cool experiment. Onto your question - probably so TBH. I might have had less reverence for his processing somewhere in my mind - but I would like to think that I would still have had the discernment to know that the mix was MONEY and that was the goal. I might have fussed with screenshots if the email chain was not stacked with heavy team members, ha, and it was only me and some dude on the thread.

I hope some of this was helpful - learning and growing every day here - I love being wrong or misinformed - means growth. Thanks for the kind words, happy to chat more about this all anytime -  "The mindset of mastering".

@Berlin is who you're asking I know (and I love his work as well)...but in my experience there is no one way. Absolutely dependent on the track. I know @Nomograph Mastering has posted on his preferences (EQ first, then limit, etc) but I'm sure even that is totally dependent on what's going on. 

I do different things on different tracks in the same day for instance, and different things within sections within those tracks sometimes. Wish that was more helpful...just trust your intuition is the best thing I can say (to both you and myself)

That said, my approach is to sorta keep as much of the essence of the mix, "do the least harm", so I try to not make any moves I don't feel pulled to. Very much...listen and wait until I feel the pull to do something. And if not, I just don't. But even then, I do wild stuff because my heart likes it. Probably where the monitoring is most important so we can just trust what we are hearing and what we are called to do

@masteredbyjack  Very thoughtful questions, I will do my best.

"sort of interested that you thought it was perhaps not cool to use the limited ref?" - This may be my location (Nashville), or training, or some mix of the artists I work for and what they expect - but the honest answer is that I can usually beat the ref, make it the same but better somehow - and to be completely transparent - for me, using the limited ref feels a bit like a cop out to me sometimes, probably more so before this experience - I don't think that's a healthy mindset but wanted to share that in the interest of transparency. I have been on both dies of the mastering thing, and I remember  getting masters back sometimes and thinking "man they really phoned that one in, sounds just like my mix" - now this opens up a whole nother convo about what mastering is or should be  - and its different project to project - but safe to say that  I was working with idiots back then, and I am willing to admit this mindset might be old school and not helpful to me anymore.

I have played that mixer role before for some time, so maybe some left over trauma from that, but when I would send a song to get mastered - I wanted the ME to BEAT my mix. Not equal it or approve it, BEAT the shit out of it haha. So perhaps that causes me some mindset of "I will do what they did but better"  - and on a technical level I find that work is easier done from the non limited mix, personally.

@Nomograph Mastering I appreciated hearing about your vinyl QC process on the general channel!

I’d be curious to hear about your typical QC for digital mastering. How many versions are you printing out (like different sample rates, etc.), and are you QC-ing each version that goes out if sending different versions? Maybe a good question to chat on the pod with @oaklandmatt 😉

(I’d also be curious to hear how others on this discord approach this)

@Nomograph Mastering I have been conviced to go the Qobuz route and am recreating my daily listening warm-up playlist out of the high res wavs (previously just had an apple music playlist).

You have any masters of yours that you think feel amazing? Like just your favorite. I have some on there now but would love to add one that you find compelling yourself! Currently have a Ruel track on there (love love love the connection to the vocal)

Also damn I am realizing how hot everything is...could sorta tell before from some other masters I've collected from mixing buds...but I'm pretty consistently about a db quieter (not true peak but in LUFS) than most of the stuff I'm finding...which I think suits the music I'm working, people are happy, I'm a more dynamic type anyway....but just interesting to note I suppose

@Will Pragnell  For me here are the two big upsides off the top of my head -

-plugin processing by clip - horsepower of computer only running per song when that song is playing.. all the plugs aren't always "on" so you can get some  extra mileage out of a CPU (at least this is my understanding)

-neat way to organize clips by "groups" and bounce them seperate or as a whole... example - vinyl sides "bounce group A" boom side a bounces... but that is quality of life !
